B.7.2 Stochastic Scheduling of Updates Between Local Free-Energies

Khan and Lin (2017) take a different approach, employing damped simplified fixed-point updates for local VI and then using an update schedule that selects a mini-batch at random and then updates the local natural parameters for these data-points in parallel. That is for all data points in the mini-batch ğ²bsubscriptğ²ğ‘\mathbf{y}_{b} they apply a single iteration of the damped simplified fixed-point updates

ğœ¼n(i)subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–ğ‘›\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{n} =(1âˆ’Ï)â€‹ğœ¼n(iâˆ’1)+Ïâ€‹ddâ€‹ğqâ€‹ğ”¼qâ€‹[logâ¡pâ€‹(yn|ğœ½)]|q=q(iâˆ’1)absent1ğœŒsubscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘›evaluated-atğœŒddsubscriptğğ‘subscriptğ”¼ğ‘delimited-[]ğ‘conditionalsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘›ğœ½ğ‘superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1\displaystyle=(1-\rho)\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{n}+\rho\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(y_{n}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}} (9)

and update the global parameters as ğœ¼q(i)=ğœ¼0+âˆ‘n:ynâˆˆğ²bğœ¼n(i)+âˆ‘nâ€²:ynâ€²âˆ‰ğ²bğœ¼nâ€²(iâˆ’1)subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–ğ‘subscriptğœ¼0subscript:ğ‘›subscriptğ‘¦ğ‘›subscriptğ²ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘›ğ‘–subscript:superscriptğ‘›â€²subscriptğ‘¦superscriptğ‘›â€²subscriptğ²ğ‘subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1superscriptğ‘›â€²\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0}+\sum_{n:y_{n}\in\mathbf{y}_{b}}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{n}^{(i)}+\sum_{n^{\prime}:y_{n^{\prime}}\notin\mathbf{y}_{b}}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{n^{\prime}}. This local update incurs a memory overhead that is Nğ‘N times larger due to the need maintain Nğ‘N sets of local parameters rather than just one. A more memory efficient approach is to fix the mini-batches across epochs and to visit the sub-groups {ğ²l}l=1Lsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ²ğ‘™ğ‘™1ğ¿\left\{\mathbf{y}_{l}\right\}_{l=1}^{L} in random order. Doing so requires storing Lğ¿L natural parameters instead, corresponding to one for each mini-batch. For simplified fixed point updates, this yields

ğœ¼l(i)subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–ğ‘™\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{l} =(1âˆ’Ï)â€‹ğœ¼l(iâˆ’1)+Ïâ€‹ddâ€‹ğqâ€‹ğ”¼qâ€‹[logâ¡pâ€‹(ğ²l|ğœ½)]|q=q(iâˆ’1)absent1ğœŒsubscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘™evaluated-atğœŒddsubscriptğğ‘subscriptğ”¼ğ‘delimited-[]ğ‘conditionalsubscriptğ²ğ‘™ğœ½ğ‘superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1\displaystyle=(1-\rho)\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}+\rho\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{l}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}} (10)

with the global parameters updated as ğœ¼q(i)=ğœ¼0+ğœ¼l(i)+âˆ‘pâ‰ lğœ¼p(iâˆ’1)subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–ğ‘subscriptğœ¼0subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–ğ‘™subscriptğ‘ğ‘™subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{0}+\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{l}+\sum_{p\neq l}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{p}. Interestingly, both of these local updates ((9) and (10)) result in a subtly different update to qâ€‹(ğœ½)ğ‘ğœ½q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) as the stochastic global update above ((8)),

ğœ¼q(i)subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–ğ‘\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}_{q} =ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)+Ïâ€‹(ddâ€‹ğqâ€‹ğ”¼qâ€‹[logâ¡pâ€‹(ğ²l|ğœ½)]|q=q(iâˆ’1)âˆ’ğœ¼l(iâˆ’1))absentsubscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘ğœŒevaluated-atddsubscriptğğ‘subscriptğ”¼ğ‘delimited-[]ğ‘conditionalsubscriptğ²ğ‘™ğœ½ğ‘superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘™\displaystyle=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{q}+\rho\left(\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}\mathbb{E}_{q}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{l}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]\right|_{q=q^{(i-1)}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}\right) (11)

where we have used ğ²lsubscriptğ²ğ‘™\mathbf{y}_{l} to denote both the sub-group and mini-batch of data. Here the deletion step is explicitly revealed again, but now it involves removing the natural parameters of the lğ‘™lth approximate likelihood ğœ¼l(iâˆ’1)subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘™\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l} rather than the average mini-batch likelihood approximation ğœ¼like(iâˆ’1)/Bsubscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1likeğµ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}/B. If the first approach in (10) employs learning rates that obey the Robins Munro conditions, the fixed points will be identical to the second approach in (11) and they will correspond to optima of the global free-energy. Note that (11) is equivalent to employing PVI and terminating the local optimisation step for sub-group ğ²lsubscriptğ²ğ‘™\mathbf{y}_{l} after a single iteration of the simplified damped fixed-point update. As discussed in SectionÂ 3, in the federated learning setting running multiple iterations of the damped simplified fixed-point updates can reduce the number of communications required. However, since we are considering stochastic approximations within local free-energy optimisations all sub-groups ğ²lsubscriptğ²ğ‘™\mathbf{y}_{l} are assumed to be stored on the same device and so the communication efficiency is irrelevant.

B.7.3 Comparing and Contrasting Stochastic Approximations

Each variety of update has its own pros and cons (compare (8) to (11)). The stochastic global update (8) does not support general online learning and distributed asynchronous updates, but it is more memory efficient and faster to converge in the batch setting.

Consider applying both methods to online learning where ğ²bsubscriptğ²ğ‘\mathbf{y}_{b} or ğ²lsubscriptğ²ğ‘™\mathbf{y}_{l} correspond to the new data seen at each stage and Ïâ€²superscriptğœŒâ€²\rho^{\prime} and ÏğœŒ\rho are user-determined learning rates for the two algorithms. General online learning poses two challenges for the stochastic global update (8). First, the data are typically not iid (due to covariate or data set shift over time). Second, general online learning does not allow all old data points to be revisited, demanding incremental updates instead. This means that when a new batch of data is received we must iterate on just these data to refine the approximate posterior, before moving on and potentially never returning. Iterating (8) on this new data is possible, but it would have disastrous consequences as it again breaks the iid mini-batch assumption and would just result in qâ€‹(ğœ½)ğ‘ğœ½q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) fitting the new data and forgetting the old previously seen data. A single update could be made, but this will normally mean that the approach is data-inefficient and slow to learn. On the other hand, iterating local updates (9) or (10) works nicely as these naturally incorporate a deletion step that removes just the contribution from the current mini-batch and can, therefore, be iterated to our heartâ€™s content.

The stochastic global update (7) does have two important advantages over the local updates (11). First, the memory footprint is Lğ¿L times smaller only requiring a single set of natural parameters to be maintained rather than Lğ¿L of them. Second, it can be faster to converge when the mini-batches are iid. Contrast what happens when new data are seen for the first time in the two approaches. For simplicity assume Ïâ€²=Ï=1superscriptğœŒâ€²ğœŒ1\rho^{\prime}=\rho=1. In the second approach, ğœ¼l(iâˆ’1)=ğŸsubscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘™0\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{0}} as the data have not been seen before, but the first approach effectively uses ğœ¼l(iâˆ’1)=ğœ¼like(iâˆ’1)/Lsubscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğ‘™subscriptsuperscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1likeğ¿\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{l}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}_{\text{like}}/L. That is, the first approach effectively estimates the approximate likelihood for new data, based on those for previously seen data. This is a sensible approximation for homogeneous mini-batches. A consequence of this is that the learning rate Ïâ€²superscriptğœŒâ€²\rho^{\prime} can be much larger than ÏğœŒ\rho (potentially greater than unity) resulting in faster convergence of the approximate posterior. It would be interesting to consider modifications of the local updates (11) that estimate the lğ‘™lth approximate likelihood based on information from all other data partitions. For example, in the first pass through the data, the approximate likelihoods for unprocessed mini-batches could be updated to be equal to the last approximate likelihood or to the geometric average of previous approximate likelihoods. Alternatively, ideas from inference networks could be employed for this purpose.

B.8 The Relationship Between Natural Gradient, Mirror-Descent, Trust-Region and Proximal Methods

Each step of gradient ascent of parameters ğœ¼ğœ¼\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}} on a cost ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} can be interpreted as the result of an optimisation problem derived from linearizing the cost function around the old parameter estimate, ğ’â€‹(ğœ¼)â‰ˆğ’â€‹(ğœ¼(iâˆ’1))+âˆ‡ğœ¼ğ’â€‹(ğœ¼(iâˆ’1))â€‹(ğœ¼âˆ’ğœ¼(iâˆ’1))ğ’ğœ¼ğ’superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1subscriptâˆ‡ğœ¼ğ’superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğœ¼superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}})\approx\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})+\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}) where âˆ‡ğœ¼ğ’â€‹(ğœ¼(iâˆ’1))=dâ€‹ğ’â€‹(ğœ¼)dâ€‹ğœ¼|ğœ¼=ğœ¼(iâˆ’1)subscriptâˆ‡ğœ¼ğ’superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1evaluated-atdğ’ğœ¼dğœ¼ğœ¼superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})=\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}})}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}} and adding a soft constraint on the norm of the parameters:

ğœ¼(i)=ğœ¼(iâˆ’1)+Ïâ€‹dâ€‹ğ’â€‹(ğœ¼)dâ€‹ğœ¼â‡”ğœ¼(i)=argâ€‹maxğœ¼â¡âˆ‡ğœ¼â¡ğ’â€‹(ğœ¼(iâˆ’1))â€‹ğœ¼âˆ’12â€‹Ïâ€‹â€–ğœ¼âˆ’ğœ¼(iâˆ’1)â€–22.â‡”superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğœŒdğ’ğœ¼dğœ¼superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–subscriptargmaxğœ¼subscriptâˆ‡ğœ¼ğ’superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–1ğœ¼12ğœŒsuperscriptsubscriptnormğœ¼superscriptğœ¼ğ‘–122\displaystyle\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}+\rho\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}})}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\;\;\Leftrightarrow\;\;\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i)}=\operatorname*{arg\,max}_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{C}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)})\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}-\frac{1}{2\rho}||\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}^{(i-1)}||_{2}^{2}.

Here the terms in the linearised cost that do not depend on ğœ¼ğœ¼\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}} have been dropped as they do not effect the solution of the optimisation problem. The linearisation of the cost ensures that there is an analytic solution to the optimisation and the soft constraint ensures that we do not move too far from the previous setting of the parameters into a region where the linearisation is inaccurate.

This reframing of gradient ascent reveals that it is making an Euclidean assumption about the geometry parameter space and suggests generalisations of the procedure that are suitable for different geometries. In our case, the parameters are natural parameters of a distribution and measures of proximity that employ the KL divergence are natural.

In the first three cases ((12) - (14)), this equivalence only holds exactly in the general case if the parameter changes Î”â€‹ğœ¼q(i)=ğœ¼q(i)âˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)Î”superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1\Delta\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)} are small.

Here the KL proximal method is the straightforward generalisation of the gradient ascent example that replaces the Euclidean norm by the exclusive KL divergence. The KL trust region method uses a hard constraint on the same KL instead, but rewriting this as a Lagrangian recovers the KL proximal method with 1/Ï1ğœŒ1/\rho being the Lagrange multiplier. The KLs trust region method, often used to justify natural gradient ascent, employs the symmetrised KL divergence instead of the exclusive KL. The symmetrised KL is the average of the exclusive and inclusive KLs, KLsâ€‹(qâ€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))=12â€‹KLâ€‹(qâ€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))+12â€‹KLâ€‹(q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥qâ€‹(ğœ½))superscriptKLsconditionalğ‘ğœ½superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½12KLconditionalğ‘ğœ½superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½12KLconditionalsuperscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½ğ‘ğœ½\mathrm{KL}^{\text{s}}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)=\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{KL}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)+\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{KL}\left(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right). Mirror descent, in its most general form, uses a Bregman divergence to control the extent to which the parameters change rather than a KL divergence. However, when applied to exponential families, the Bregman divergence becomes the inclusive KL divergence yielding the form above (Raskutti and Mukherjee, 2015; Khan etÂ al., 2016; Khan and Lin, 2017). Note that this last method operates in the mean parameter space and the equivalence is attained by mapping the mean parameter updates back to the natural parameters. Mirror descent has the advantage of not relying on the small parameter change assumption to recover natural gradient ascent. Having explained the rationale behind these approaches we will now sketch how they yield the fixed-point updates.

The equivalence of the KL proximal method can be shown by differentiating the cost w.r.t. ğœ¼qsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q} and substituting in the following expressions:

dKLâ€‹(qâ€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))dâ€‹ğœ¼qdKLconditionalğ‘ğœ½superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½dsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘\displaystyle\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathrm{KL}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}} =dâ€‹ğqdâ€‹ğœ¼qâ€‹(ğœ¼qâˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1))â‰ˆdâ€‹ğq(iâˆ’1)dâ€‹ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ¼qâˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)).absentdsubscriptğğ‘dsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘subscriptğœ¼ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1dsubscriptğsuperscriptğ‘ğ‘–1dsubscriptğœ¼superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1subscriptğœ¼ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1\displaystyle=\frac{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right)\approx\frac{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right).

In the second line above the approximation results from the assumption of small parameter change Î”â€‹ğœ¼q(i)Î”superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–\Delta\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)} (or alternatively local constancy of the Fisher information). Equating the derivatives to zero and rearranging recovers the fixed point equations.

The equivalence of the KL trust region method is now simple to show as the associated Lagrangian, â„’â€‹(ğœ¼q)=âˆ‡ğœ¼â„±k(i)â€‹(q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))â€‹ğœ¼qâˆ’1Ïâ€‹(KLâ€‹(qâ€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))âˆ’Î³)â„’subscriptğœ¼ğ‘subscriptâˆ‡ğœ¼subscriptsuperscriptâ„±ğ‘–ğ‘˜superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½subscriptğœ¼ğ‘1ğœŒKLconditionalğ‘ğœ½superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½ğ›¾\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q})=\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\frac{1}{\rho}\left(\mathrm{KL}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)-\gamma\right), is the proximal method up to an additive constant.

Similarly, the KLs trust region method can also be rewritten as a Lagrangian â„’â€‹(ğœ¼q)=âˆ‡ğœ¼â„±k(i)â€‹(q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))â€‹ğœ¼qâˆ’1Ïâ€‹(KLsâ€‹(qâ€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))âˆ’Î³)â„’subscriptğœ¼ğ‘subscriptâˆ‡ğœ¼subscriptsuperscriptâ„±ğ‘–ğ‘˜superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½subscriptğœ¼ğ‘1ğœŒsuperscriptKLsconditionalğ‘ğœ½superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½ğ›¾\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q})=\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}}\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\frac{1}{\rho}\left(\mathrm{KL}^{\text{s}}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)-\gamma\right). For small changes in the approximate posterior natural parameters Î”â€‹ğœ¼q(i)=ğœ¼q(i)âˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)Î”superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1\Delta\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}, the symmetrised KL can be approximated using a second order Taylor expansion,

KLsâ€‹(qâ€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))â‰ˆ12â€‹(ğœ¼qâˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1))âŠ¤â€‹dâ€‹ğq(iâˆ’1)dâ€‹ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ¼qâˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1)).superscriptKLsconditionalğ‘ğœ½superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½12superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1topdsubscriptğsuperscriptğ‘ğ‘–1dsubscriptğœ¼superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1subscriptğœ¼ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1\displaystyle\mathrm{KL}^{\text{s}}\left(q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)\approx\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right)^{\top}\frac{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}\left(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}\right).

This is the same form as the exclusive KL takes, the inclusive and exclusive KL divergences being locally identical around their optima. Taking derivatives of the Lagrangian and setting them to zero recovers the fixed point equations again.

The mirror descent method can be shown to yield the fixed points by noting that

âˆ‡ğâ„±k(i)â€‹(q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½))subscriptâˆ‡ğsubscriptsuperscriptâ„±ğ‘–ğ‘˜superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½\displaystyle\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}}\mathcal{F}^{(i)}_{k}(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})) =ddâ€‹ğq(iâˆ’1)â€‹ğ”¼q(iâˆ’1)â€‹[logâ¡pâ€‹(ğ²k|ğœ½)]âˆ’ğœ¼k,absentddsubscriptğsuperscriptğ‘ğ‘–1subscriptğ”¼superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1delimited-[]ğ‘conditionalsubscriptğ²ğ‘˜ğœ½subscriptğœ¼ğ‘˜\displaystyle=\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q^{(i-1)}}}\mathbb{E}_{q^{(i-1)}}\left[\log p(\mathbf{y}_{k}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right]-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{k},
dKLâ€‹(q(iâˆ’1)â€‹(ğœ½)âˆ¥qâ€‹(ğœ½))dâ€‹ğqdKLconditionalsuperscriptğ‘ğ‘–1ğœ½ğ‘ğœ½dsubscriptğğ‘\displaystyle\frac{\mathrm{d}\mathrm{KL}\left(q^{(i-1)}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})~{}\|~{}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})\right)}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\mu}}_{q}} =ğœ¼qâˆ’ğœ¼q(iâˆ’1).absentsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğœ¼ğ‘ğ‘–1\displaystyle=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}-\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\eta}}_{q}^{(i-1)}.

Differentiating the mirror descent objective and substituting these results in recovers usual update. The last result above can be found using convex duality. For a full derivation and more information on the relationship between mirror descent and natural gradients see Raskutti and Mukherjee (2015).

It is also possible to define optimisation approaches analogous to the above that do not linearise the free-energy term and instead perform potentially multiple updates of the nested non-linear optimisation problems (Theis and Hoffman, 2015; Khan etÂ al., 2015, 2016; Khan and Lin, 2017).

C Gradients of the Free-Energy With Respect to Hyperparameters

In this section, we derive the gradients of the global free energy w.r.t.Â the hyperparameters for general qâ€‹(ğœ½)ğ‘ğœ½q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}).

The global free-energy depends on the model hyperparameters through the joint distribution pâ€‹(ğ²,ğœ½|Ïµ)ğ‘ğ²conditionalğœ½bold-italic-Ïµp(\mathbf{y},\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}|\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}),

C.2 Derivation for Collapsed Bound

In this section, we consider the setting in which qâ€‹(ğœ½)ğ‘ğœ½q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) is the optimal variational approximation for a fixed setting of the hyperparameters, so depends implicitly on Ïµbold-italic-Ïµ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}:

Note that here we have been careful to represent the two distinct ways that the free-energy depends on the hyperparameters: 1) through the log-jointâ€™s dependence; and 2) through the optimal approximate posteriorâ€™s implicit dependence. Taking derivatives w.r.t.Â Ïµbold-italic-Ïµ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} gives

ddâ€‹Ïµâ€‹â„±â€‹(Ïµ,qâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµ))=ddâ€‹Ïµâ€‹â„±â€‹(Ïµ,qâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµâ€²))|Ïµâ€²=Ïµ+ddâ€‹Ïµâ€²â€‹â„±â€‹(Ïµ,qâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµâ€²))|Ïµâ€²=Ïµ.ddbold-italic-Ïµâ„±bold-italic-Ïµğ‘ğœ½bold-italic-Ïµevaluated-atddbold-italic-Ïµâ„±bold-italic-Ïµğ‘ğœ½superscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²superscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²bold-italic-Ïµevaluated-atddsuperscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²â„±bold-italic-Ïµğ‘ğœ½superscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²superscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²bold-italic-Ïµ\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}))=\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}+\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}.

The first captures the dependence through the log-joint distribution and is given by

The second term captures the dependence through the optimal approximate posteriorâ€™s implicit dependence on Ïµbold-italic-Ïµ\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}} and is given by

ddâ€‹Ïµâ€²â€‹â„±â€‹(Ïµ,qâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµâ€²))|Ïµâ€²=Ïµ=dqâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµ)dâ€‹Ïµâ€²â€‹ddâ€‹qâ€‹(ğœ½)â€‹â„±â€‹(Ïµ,qâ€‹(ğœ½))|Ïµâ€²=Ïµ,qâ€‹(ğœ½)=qâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµ)=ğŸ.evaluated-atddsuperscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²â„±bold-italic-Ïµğ‘ğœ½superscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²superscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²bold-italic-Ïµevaluated-atdqğœ½bold-italic-Ïµdsuperscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²ddğ‘ğœ½â„±bold-italic-Ïµğ‘ğœ½formulae-sequencesuperscriptbold-italic-Ïµâ€²bold-italic-Ïµğ‘ğœ½ğ‘ğœ½bold-italic-Ïµ0\left.\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}}=\left.\frac{\mathrm{dq(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}}{\mathrm{d}\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}}\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})}\mathcal{F}(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}))\right|_{\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}},q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}})=q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}})}=\boldsymbol{\mathbf{0}}.

Here, we have used the fact that we are at the collapsed bound and so the functional derivative w.r.t.Â qâ€‹(ğœ½)ğ‘ğœ½q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) is zero. Thus, for both the general qâ€‹(ğœ½)ğ‘ğœ½q(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}}) and optimal qâ€‹(ğœ½;Ïµ)ğ‘ğœ½bold-italic-Ïµq(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\theta}};\boldsymbol{\mathbf{\epsilon}}), we obtain the same expression for gradients of the global free-energy w.r.t.Â the hyperparameters.

FigureÂ 9 provides some intuition for these results. Note that in the case where the approximating family includes the true posterior distribution, the collapsed bound is equal to the log-likelihood of the hyperparameters. So, the result shows that the gradient of the log-likelihood w.r.t. the hyperparameters is equal to the gradient of the free-energy w.r.t. the hyperparameters, treating qğ‘q as fixed. Often this is computed in the M-step of variational EM, but it is used in coordinate ascent, which can be slow to converge. Instead, this gradient can be passed to an optimiser to perform direct gradient-based optimisation of the log-likelihood.

D Forms of Inhomogeneity

Throughout this paper we have used the blanket term â€˜inhomogeneousâ€™ to describe a variety of different forms of inhomogeneity across data partitions. This section sheds light on the different forms of inhomogeneity and describes the suitability of PVI, and more generally federated learning, in the presence of each. Each clientâ€™s dataset is assumed to be sampled according to a local dataset distribution ğ’«mâ€‹(ğ±,y)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šğ±ğ‘¦\mathcal{P}_{m}(\mathbf{x},y), and we consider the task of learning a discriminative model pâ€‹(y|ğ±)ğ‘conditionalğ‘¦ğ±p(y|\mathbf{x})191919If instead we consider the task of learning a generative model pâ€‹(ğ±,y)ğ‘ğ±ğ‘¦p(\mathbf{x},y), then it would be advantageous to learn personalised models in the presence of covariate shift.. We consider three distinct sources of inhomogeneity:

  1. 1.

    the local dataset distributions differ between clients;

  2. 2.

    the size of local datasets differ between clients;

  3. 3.

    the available compute differs between clients.

If the local dataset distributions are the same between clients, then learning a shared model through federated learning is advantageous. However, there are a number of ways in which local dataset distributions can differ. The first is covariate shift, in which the marginal distributions ğ’«mâ€‹(ğ±)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šğ±\mathcal{P}_{m}(\mathbf{x}) and ğ’«mâ€‹(y)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šğ‘¦\mathcal{P}_{m}(y) differ between clients whilst ğ’«mâ€‹(y|ğ±)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šconditionalğ‘¦ğ±\mathcal{P}_{m}(y|\mathbf{x}) are shared. Since we are concerned with modelling the discriminative distribution pâ€‹(y|ğ±)ğ‘conditionalğ‘¦ğ±p(y|\mathbf{x}), the use federated learning of a single, shared model in this setting seems advantageous as data from each client provides us with information about the relationship between inputs and outputs. However, as we tend to use parametric models of fixed capacity it may be preferable to learn personalised models which more accurately model the discriminative distribution for inputs with high probability under ğ’«mâ€‹(ğ±)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šğ±\mathcal{P}_{m}(\mathbf{x}). When the conditional distributions ğ’«mâ€‹(y|ğ±)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šconditionalğ‘¦ğ±\mathcal{P}_{m}(y|\mathbf{x}) differ between clients, it is clearly desirable to learn a personalised discriminative model for each client which models the local conditional distribution ğ’«mâ€‹(y|ğ±)subscriptğ’«ğ‘šconditionalğ‘¦ğ±\mathcal{P}_{m}(y|\mathbf{x}). However, although local dataset distributions may differ, they may be similar to the extent that it is still useful to share information between clients without assuming the same model for eachâ€”this describes the personalised federated learning setting.

E.2 Mortality Prediction

The five splits used in the mortality prediction experiment are detailed in TableÂ 3. These were obtained by performing k-means clustering on the input features, and can thus be interpreted as having different dataset distributions.

The variational objectives were optimised using the Adam optimiser (Kingma and Ba, 2014b) with a batch size of 128 and a learning rate of 1Ã—10âˆ’31superscript1031\times 10^{-3} for both the logistic regression and BNN experiments.

E.3 Federated MNIST

The variational objectives were optimised using the Adam optimiser (Kingma and Ba, 2014b) with a batch size of 512 and a learning rate of 2Ã—10âˆ’32superscript1032\times 10^{-3}.

In FigureÂ 10, we compare the performance of the stochastic implementation of global VI in which we visit a single client at a time performing an update of the approximate posterior using a biased estimate of the ELBO. This achieves faster initial convergence than sequential PVI, which can be attributed to the difficulty of learning approximate factors in the presence of severe inhomogeneity.

In FigureÂ 11, we compare the number of synchronous gradient steps performed by each of the federated learning algorithms. If the time taken to communicate between the server and clients is ignored, then this serves as a proxy for the run time of each method. Sequential methods are the slowest as they do not update clients in parallel.

FiguresÂ 12 andÂ 13 compare the effect the damping factor ÏğœŒ\rho has on the convergence of sequential and synchronous PVI for the homogeneous MNIST classification task. For sequential PVI, less damping results in faster convergence. The same is not true for synchronous PVI: using less damping results in faster convergence for Ï<0.25ğœŒ0.25\rho<0.25. For Ïâ‰¥0.25ğœŒ0.25\rho\geq 0.25, the aggregation of approximate factors does not result in a normalisable distribution and the performance diverges.
